Kubernets Security Primitives: 
Secure kubernetes by who can access it? What they can do once they access it?
A. Authentication - who can access? Using Static token file, certificate, service accounts, LDAP(External authentication providers)
B. Authorization - What they can do? using RBAC, ABAC, Node Authoization, Webhook mode
C. TLS Certificates - Each components in the cluster can communicate to Kube-APIServer using certificate by configuring tls certificate.
D. Network Policies - To restrict the pod communication from the one node to other pods in the other node using network policies. 


1. Authentication - who can access? Using Static token file, certificate, service accounts, LDAP(External authentication providers)

Admin: Admin will access cluster for administrative task.
Developers: Developers will access the cluster to deploy the application on the cluster.
End Users: access to applications in the cluster
Bots: Third party services can access k8s cluster.

Service Account: Bots
Diffecrent secure mechanism for the application in the cluster: End users
Static token file: Admin & Developers

Static token file is csv format which has the details like password, username, userid, groupid. 
Note: Static toke file authentication is not a recommended mechanism for securing the kubernetes cluster.


